## Main Text: where all text goes (Required)
Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
A researcher is interested in estimating the mean of a large population and gathers a random sample of $n[0] observations, but loses the records of the last $m[0]. Thus only $diff[0] observations are available for calculating the sample mean. What is the efficiency of this sample mean, relative to what could have been obtained from the whole sample? The relative efficiency is deÂ…fined here using the larger variance in the numerator. Round off your answer to two decimal places.  \{  ans_rule(7) \} 
END_TEXT
#########################################################
## Answers evaluation (Required)
ANS( num_cmp($q1ans, tol=> 0.02) );

#########################################################
## Solution (Optional but recommended)
Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_SOLUTION
If \(X\) denotes the sample mean, then the sample mean is unbiased for the population mean regardless of sample size. For a sample of size $n[0],
$BR
$BCENTER
\(
Var(\bar{X}) = \frac{ \sigma^2 }{ $n[0]}
\)
$ECENTER
$BR
where \( \sigma^2 \) is the population variance. In this case we compare the variance of the two sample means based on sample sizes $diff[0] and $n[0], the relative efficiency being
$BR
$BR
$BCENTER
\begin{align} 
\frac{ Var( \bar{X}_{$diff[0]}) }{ Var( \bar{X}_{$n[0]}) } &= \frac{ \sigma^2/$diff[0] }{ \sigma^2/$n[0]} \\
&=\frac{$n[0]}{$diff[0]} \\
&=$q1ans.   
\end{align}
$ECENTER
$BR
Recall that the sampling distribution of \( \bar{X} \) gets tighter about the population mean as the sample size increases, which tells us the mean from the larger sample will have the lower variance.
END_SOLUTION
